He helped set up a Rapid Reaction Corps, which saw him lead UN interventions in the Balkans conflict. After Sandhurst, Peter Inge was commissioned into the Green Howards in 1956 and rose through the ranks. He retired from the Army in 1997 and was made a life peer. A big critic of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, he warned there had not been enough strategic thinking. In 1960 he married Letitia Thornton-Berry who pre-deceased him. He is survived by their two daughters.